The paper deals with the decoding of codes, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). It specifically focuses on spatially coupled codes, which are a type of low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes, and discusses their properties related to linear programming (LP) decoding. This makes it relevant to the sub-category of coding theory (cs.CC). The paper also introduces and proves properties related to dual witnesses for LP decoding, which involves graph theory and optimization, making it relevant to the sub-categories of discrete mathematics (cs.DS) and optimization and control (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the trade-off between crossover probability and LP excess, which is relevant to the sub-category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI).
